	<text>
		<body>
			<p><persName ref="#ehri_et_munzer_efroim">Efroim Münzer</persName> Testimony (doc. 301/203)</p>

			<p>Original, manuscript, 4 pages, 150 x 210 mm, Polish language</p>

			<p><pb n="1" facs="EHRI-ET-ZIH3010203_01.jpg"/><persName ref="#ehri_et_munzer_efroim">Efroim Münzer</persName>, born <date
					when="1928-01-01">1. 1. 1928</date> in <placeName ref="http://www.geonames.org/772270/gdow.html">Gdów</placeName>, a town in
					<placeName ref="http://www.geonames.org/7533001/wieliczka.html">Wieliczka</placeName> district</p>
			<p>Occupation: baker</p>
			<p>Residence: <placeName ref="http://www.geonames.org/3094802/krakow.html">66/17 Starowiślna [Street]</placeName> in <placeName
					ref="http://www.geonames.org/3094802/krakow.html">Cracow</placeName></p>
			<p>Description of the <term ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-508" type="subject">camp</term> and <term
					ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-486" type="subject">life</term> in <placeName
					ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_camps-1878" type="camp">Stalowa Wola</placeName></p>
			<p>He stayed in the <term ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-508" type="subject">camp</term> from <date when="1942"
					>1942</date> to <date when="1944">1944</date>. In <date when="1942-08">August 1942</date>, during a <term
					ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-115" type="subject">deportation</term> in <placeName
					ref="http://www.geonames.org/7533001/wieliczka.html">Wieliczka</placeName>, they were loaded onto <term
					ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-522" type="subject">cattle cars</term>, 100 people in each. He rode on a
					<term ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-522" type="subject">train</term> for 24 hours during a very hot
				period and nobody was allowed to approach them with something to drink. Only in <placeName
					ref="http://www.geonames.org/7531275/debica.html">Dębica</placeName> a <term type="subject" ref="#ehri_et_nationalities_poles"
					>Pole</term> gave them a bucket of water at the <term ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-660" type="subject"
					>charge</term> of 100 złotys. On the arrival in <term ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-508" type="subject"
					>camp</term>, they were received by the <term ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-480" type="subject">camp
					guards</term> consisting of <term type="subject" ref="#ehri_et_nationalities_belarusians">Belorussians</term> with <term
					ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-564" type="subject">whips</term>. There were 3 <term
					ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-837" type="subject">barracks</term> for the <term
					ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-1057" type="subject">laborers</term>. In <date when="1942-08">August
					1942</date> there were 80 Jews from <placeName ref="http://www.geonames.org/759301/sieniawa.html">Sieniawa</placeName> there.
				Since <date when="1942-08">August</date>, there were already 680 (600 from <placeName
					ref="http://www.geonames.org/7533001/wieliczka.html">Wieliczka</placeName>). The bunks in the <term
					ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-837" type="subject">barrack</term> had no paillasses, so that the <term
					ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-558" type="subject">laborers</term> slept on the boards. On the first day
				the <term ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-1057" type="subject">workers</term>
				<term ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-653" type="subject">stood</term> in front of the <term
					ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-837" type="subject">barrack</term> from five in the morning till the
				evening. During that time they were thoroughly searched and deprived of <pb n="2" facs="EHRI-ET-ZIH3010203_02.jpg"/> everything, from
					<term ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-660" type="subject">money</term> and valuables down to a simple
				leather belt. In the evening the <term ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-1216" type="subject">SS</term>
				<foreign xml:lang="de">Scharführer</foreign>
				<persName ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/authorities/ehri_pers-000364">Schwamberg</persName> (known as the <term
					ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-551" type="subject">liquidator</term> of the <placeName
					ref="http://www.geonames.org/7530748/przemysl.html">Przemyśl</placeName>
				<term ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-546" type="subject">ghetto</term>) and the <foreign xml:lang="de"
					>Unterscharführer</foreign>
				<persName ref="#ehri_et_bardok">Brzdok</persName> (probably <persName ref="#ehri_et_bardok">Bardok</persName>) came to them. <persName
					ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/authorities/ehri_pers-000364">Schwamberg</persName> gave a speech: They have to give away all
				the valuables. Whoever should go near the fence will automatically be <term
					ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-541" type="subject">shot</term>. Whichever of the Jews talks to a civilian
				during work, be it about the sale of <term type="subject" ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-832">bread</term> or
				anything else, will be <term ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-541" type="subject">shot</term>. Whoever pauses
				at work, will be <term ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-541" type="subject">shot</term>.</p>
			<p>Directly after this speech, the majority threw away the money or <term ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-660"
					type="subject">valuables</term> they were hiding. In the meantime, as a warning, they <term
					ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-653" type="subject">beat</term> several people till blood was drawn,
				supposedly because they hadn’t given away everything. There was a <term ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-486"
					type="subject">reveille</term> at two in the night. They marched out to <term
					ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-943" type="subject">work</term> at 6; till then they were kept standing.
				They were taken away their caps and jackets to prevent them from <term ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-204"
					type="subject">escaping</term>. On the way to <term ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-943" type="subject"
					>work</term> in a <term ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-944" type="subject">factory</term> distant by 4 km
				they were driven <pb n="3" facs="EHRI-ET-ZIH3010203_03.jpg"/> with <term ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-564"
					type="subject">whips</term>. They had to run all the way. They <term ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-943"
					type="subject">worked</term> from 7 am to 6 pm with one 20-minute break at 3 pm for a <term
					ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-832" type="subject">soup</term>. They <term
					ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-943" type="subject">worked</term> in a steelworks. <foreign xml:lang="de"
					>Vorarbeiters</foreign>
				<note type="gloss">Vorarbeiter (German) – foreman.</note> at <term ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-943"
					type="subject">work</term> were <term ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-1075" type="subject"
					>Volksdeutsche</term>. The greatest sadist among them was <persName ref="#ehri_et_piosik">Piosik</persName> (rumored to come from
					<placeName ref="http://www.geonames.org/7530858/poznan.html">Poznań</placeName>). He <term type="subject"
					ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-532">murdered</term> the Jews with a <term
					ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-533" type="subject">piece</term> of iron. He once <term
					ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-533" type="subject">burned</term> a Jew alive. Most Jews <term
					ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-745" type="subject">died</term> because of the said <persName
					ref="#ehri_et_piosik">Piosik</persName>. Almost 8-10 Jews <term ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-204"
					type="subject">escaped</term> everyday from the workplace. Because of that almost every day they had to <term
					ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-653" type="subject">stand</term> 2-3 hours at <term
					ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-487" type="subject">roll call</term>. In the evening they were given
				ab[out] <term ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-834" type="subject">20dkg</term> of <term type="subject"
					ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-832">bread</term> and a <term type="subject"
					ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-832">soup</term>, in which there were <term
					ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-832" type="subject">dirty</term> and unpeeled <term type="subject"
					ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-832">potatoes</term>. At the head of a <term
					ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-837" type="subject">barrack</term> stood an <foreign xml:lang="de"
					>Ordnungsdienstmann</foreign>. <note type="gloss">Ordnungsdienstmann (German) – member of the Ordnungsdienst (Order
					Service)</note> Almost everyday 10-15 of the <term ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-292" type="subject"
					>sick</term>, who lay in the so called <foreign xml:lang="de">Krankenstube</foreign>, <note type="gloss">Krankenstube (German) -
					sickroom</note>were <term ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-541" type="subject">shot</term>. These <term
					ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-541" type="subject">murders</term> were committed by an <term
					ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-1216" type="subject">SS</term>-<foreign xml:lang="de">Sturmmann</foreign>.
				In <date when="1942-12">December 1942</date>, 121 or 123 Jews were <term ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-541"
					type="subject">shot</term> as unfit for <term ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-943" type="subject"
					>work</term>. Apart from that, 10-15 <term ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-862" type="subject"
					>people</term>
				<term ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-745" type="subject">died</term> every day (<term
					ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-494" type="subject">dysentery</term> and the like). (Since <date
					when="1942-09">September</date> there were already <term ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-862"
					type="subject">1100</term> Jews). <pb n="4" facs="EHRI-ET-ZIH3010203_04.jpg"/> At the head of the <term
					ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-566" type="subject">OD</term>
				<note type="gloss">OD - Ordnungsdienst</note> there stood a <term type="subject" ref="#ehri_et_nationalities_germans">German</term>
				Jew, <persName ref="#ehri_et_goldstein_lindenmann">Goldstein-Lindenmann</persName>, a <term
					ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-840" type="subject">pervert</term>, an <term
					ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-1216" type="subject">SS</term>-<foreign xml:lang="de"
				>Sturmmann</foreign>’s favorite (He is rumored to be under <term type="subject"
					ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-598">arrest</term> now). At the end of <date when="1942">1942</date> only
				300 Jews remained, who <term ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-943" type="subject">worked</term> already under
				the <orgName ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/authorities/ehri_cb-438">Wehrmacht’s</orgName> supervision. After 80 Jews from
					<placeName ref="http://www.geonames.org/7530748/przemysl.html">Przemyśl</placeName>
				<term ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-521" type="subject">arrived</term> (in <date when="1942-12">December
					1942</date>), there were already 380 Jews. This situation didn’t change until <term
					ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-573" type="subject">the end</term>. Once, when two Jews accused the said
					<persName ref="#ehri_et_goldstein_lindenmann">Goldstein-Lindenmann</persName> of <term
					ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-562" type="subject">beating</term> the Jews, he <term type="subject"
					ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-200">denounced</term> their supposed intention of <term
					ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-204" type="subject">escape</term>. They were <term
					ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-541" type="subject">shot</term>. In <date when="1943-03">March 1943</date>
				he prepared a list of 56 Jews who, as he claimed, were unable to <term ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-943"
					type="subject">work</term>. They were <term ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-541" type="subject"
					>shot</term>. In <date when="1944-07">July 1944</date>, during the <orgName
					ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/authorities/ehri_cb-004583">Soviet offensive</orgName>, most people wanted to <term
					ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-204" type="subject">escape</term>, but were prevented by <persName
					ref="#ehri_et_goldstein_lindenmann">Goldstein</persName>. And yet 85 Jews pulled out the fences, cut the barbed wire with scissors
				and <term ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-204" type="subject">ran away</term> into the <term
					ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-265" type="subject">forest</term>. They <term
					ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-262" type="subject">stayed</term> there for 2 weeks (until <date
					when="1945-08-02">August 2</date>). They were <term ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-573" type="subject"
					>liberated</term> by the <orgName ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/authorities/ehri_cb-004583">Soviets</orgName>.</p>
